{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LwjEndu437Fs5JFmpAhBNm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche System Design\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→Cloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\n     6→environments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\n     7→agentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n     8→\n     9→This document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n    10→\n    11→## System Components\n    12→\n    13→Cloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→cmd/\n    17→  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n    18→  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n    19→  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→### cloche (CLI)\n    23→\n    24→Short-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n    25→\n    26→Subcommands:\n    27→- `run <workflow>` — Launch a new workflow run\n    28→- `status [run-id]` — Check run status\n    29→- `logs <run-id>` — Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n    30→- `stop <run-id>` — Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n    31→\n    32→Accepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n    33→\n    34→### cloched (Daemon)\n    35→\n    36→Long-running process. Responsibilities:\n    37→- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n    38→- Listen to status streams from running agents\n    39→- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n    40→- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n    41→- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n    42→\n    43→The daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\n    44→and collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n    45→\n    46→### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n    47→\n    48→Autonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n    49→- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n    50→- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n    51→- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n    52→- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n    53→- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n    54→\n    55→The agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n    56→\n    57→## Communication\n    58→\n    59→### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n    60→\n    61→- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n    62→- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n    63→- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n    64→\n    65→### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n    66→\n    67→- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n    68→- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n    69→- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n    70→- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n    71→\n    72→## Workflow DSL\n    73→\n    74→### Vocabulary\n    75→\n    76→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    77→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    78→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    79→| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n    80→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    81→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    82→| done     | Built-in terminal step indicating successful completion            |\n    83→| abort    | Built-in terminal step indicating failure (reports error and exits)|\n    84→\n    85→### Syntax\n    86→\n    87→```\n    88→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    89→  step code {\n    90→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n    91→    container {\n    92→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    93→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"internal-docs.company.com\"]\n    94→    }\n    95→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    96→  }\n    97→\n    98→  step check {\n    99→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n   100→    results = [pass, fail]\n   101→  }\n   102→\n   103→  step review {\n   104→    prompt = file(\"prompts/review.md\")\n   105→    input = step.code.output\n   106→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n   107→  }\n   108→\n   109→  code:success -> check\n   110→  code:fail -> abort\n   111→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n   112→\n   113→  check:pass -> review\n   114→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n   115→\n   116→  review:approved -> done\n   117→  review:changes_requested -> code\n   118→}\n   119→```\n   120→\n   121→### Key Properties\n   122→\n   123→- Step type is inferred from content: `prompt` field → agent step, `run` field → script step.\n   124→- Steps declare which results they can emit. The step decides at runtime which result to report.\n   125→- Wiring is separate from step definitions. This enables runtime injection of new steps\n   126→  (the self-evolution feature) — insert a new check between existing steps by rewiring,\n   127→  without modifying either step.\n   128→- `file()` loads external content (prompt files, scripts).\n   129→- Step inputs can reference other step outputs (`step.code.output`).\n   130→- The graph engine validates at parse time: all declared results are wired, no orphan steps,\n   131→  entry point exists.\n   132→\n   133→## Hexagonal Architecture\n   134→\n   135→The core domain is independent of Docker, gRPC, SQLite, or any other infrastructure.\n   136→\n   137→### Domain\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→internal/domain/\n   141→  workflow.go    # Workflow, Step, Result, Graph types\n   142→  run.go         # Run, RunState, StepExecution types\n   143→  capture.go     # CapturedInput, CapturedOutput for replay\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→### Ports (interfaces)\n   147→\n   148→```\n   149→internal/ports/\n   150→  store.go       # RunStore, WorkflowStore, CaptureStore\n   151→  container.go   # ContainerRuntime (start, stop, attach, logs)\n   152→  agent.go       # AgentAdapter (how to invoke an agent)\n   153→  notifier.go    # StatusNotifier (how to report progress)\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→### Adapters (implementations)\n   157→\n   158→```\n   159→internal/adapters/\n   160→  docker/        # ContainerRuntime via Docker API\n   161→  sqlite/        # Store implementations via SQLite\n   162→  grpc/          # gRPC server (daemon) and client (CLI)\n   163→  agents/\n   164→    claudecode/  # AgentAdapter for Claude Code\n   165→    generic/     # AgentAdapter for arbitrary commands\n   166→```\n   167→\n   168→### Key Interfaces\n   169→\n   170→- **ContainerRuntime** — Start/stop containers, attach to stdout, copy files in/out.\n   171→  Docker today, Podman or Firecracker later.\n   172→- **RunStore** — Persist run state (active step, reported results, timestamps).\n   173→- **CaptureStore** — Store step inputs/outputs for replay. Git refs serve as pointers\n   174→  to file states; metadata lives in the store.\n   175→- **AgentAdapter** — Translates between Cloche's step protocol and a specific agent's\n   176→  interface. Claude Code adapter knows how to invoke `claude` CLI. Generic adapter runs\n   177→  any command.\n   178→- **StatusNotifier** — How the agent reports progress. Stdout JSON-lines initially.\n   179→\n   180→## Container Model\n   181→\n   182→### One Container Per Workflow Run\n   183→\n   184→A container is spun up for a workflow run. All steps execute inside the same container.\n   185→File state accumulates naturally across steps (agent modifies code, then test script\n   186→runs against those modifications).\n   187→\n   188→### Lifecycle\n   189→\n   190→1. `cloched` pulls/builds the container image\n   191→2. Copies project files into the container at `/workspace`\n   192→3. Starts the container with `cloche-agent` as entrypoint, passing the workflow name\n   193→4. `cloche-agent` parses the workflow, walks the graph, executes steps\n   194→5. Agent streams status events to `cloched` via stdout\n   195→6. At step boundaries, modified files are pushed to the host via git (agent-specific branch)\n   196→7. On completion (`done`/`abort`), container is stopped\n   197→\n   198→### File Extraction via Git\n   199→\n   200→The container's git remote is configured to push to the host repository. Each run pushes\n   201→to a unique branch (e.g. `cloche/run-<id>/step-<name>`). This provides:\n   202→- Full git history of what the agent did\n   203→- Trivial diffs between input and output states\n   204→- Clean branch-per-step organization\n   205→- No bind mounts (maintains isolation)\n   206→\n   207→### Security Boundaries\n   208→\n   209→1. **Filesystem** — No access beyond `/workspace`. Copy-in at start, git push for extraction.\n   210→2. **Network** — `--network none` by default. If `network_allow` is specified, Cloche creates\n   211→   a custom Docker network restricting egress to allowlisted domains via DNS proxy.\n   212→3. **Environment** — Configured in Dockerfile/image. Cloche does not inject env vars.\n   213→\n   214→## Capture System\n   215→\n   216→Each step execution is captured for later inspection and replay.\n   217→\n   218→### What Gets Captured\n   219→\n   220→- Step config (prompt, type, container settings)\n   221→- Input state (git ref of what was provided to the step)\n   222→- Output state (git ref of what the step produced)\n   223→- Result reported (which result name)\n   224→- Stdout/stderr logs\n   225→- Timing metadata\n   226→\n   227→### Storage\n   228→\n   229→Metadata in the store (SQLite initially). Git refs serve as pointers to actual file\n   230→states — no duplication of file content.\n   231→\n   232→## MVP Scope (v0.1)\n   233→\n   234→### In Scope\n   235→\n   236→- `cloche` CLI: `run`, `status`, `logs`, `stop`\n   237→- `cloched` daemon: container lifecycle, status collection, gRPC API, SQLite store\n   238→- `cloche-agent`: DSL parser, graph engine, agent/script execution, status reporting\n   239→- Workflow DSL: steps, results, wiring, `done`/`abort` terminals, `file()` references\n   240→- Container model: Docker, copy-in project files, git push for extraction, network allowlist\n   241→- Agent adapters: Generic (run a command) + Claude Code\n   242→- Capture system: Record step inputs/outputs/results\n   243→\n   244→### Post-MVP\n   245→\n   246→- Self-evolution: failure pattern analysis, automatic step injection into workflows\n   247→- Replay system: partial/full/dry replay of captured runs\n   248→- Auto-split commits into stacked branches\n   249→- Additional agent adapters\n   250→- Alternative storage backends (Postgres, DynamoDB)\n   251→- Alternative container runtimes (Podman, Firecracker)\n   252→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kwo4Gqf8Kyz3LgA9JjACuj","session_id":"caefa047-41e4-4a64-a92e-dbea2379cd5a","uuid":"18ca87c5-f1e7-4f6b-bd0f-0df6e0b1246c"}
